"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:3.1.2.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">3.1.2.2</span> Key</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מַפְתֵּחַ</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mafteach)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg3:25\">JDG 3:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr9:27\">1CH 9:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa22:22\">ISA 22:22</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">κλείς</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kleis)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt16:19\">MAT 16:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke11:52\">LUK 11:52</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev1:18\">REV 1:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev3:7\">REV 3:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev9:1\">REV 9:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev20:1\">REV 20:1</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0404_key.jpg\" alt=\"Roman era key\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Roman era key (© Hermann Junghans, CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The key was an instrument used for locking and unlocking doors and gates. Ancient keys were generally much larger than anything commonly known today.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0405_keys.jpg\" alt=\"Ancient Roman keys (Archaeological park Ruffenhofen: Limeseum)\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Ancient Roman keys (Archaeological park Ruffenhofen: Limeseum) (© Wolfgang Sauber, CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>Keys are not always well known, so some translators may have to use a descriptive phrase, such as “object that controls whether a door can be opened.” Sometimes it is possible to render “key” by describing its function, for example, “unlocker” or “means to open.”</p>\n<p>Except for <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg3:25\">JDG 3:25</a>, all the references to “key” listed above are symbolic. Nevertheless, all translations consulted use the word “key” even in the symbolic contexts. Note the expansion of <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Italian Common Language Version\">ITCL</abbr> at <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa22:22\">ISA 22:22</a>: where the text says literally “I will place on his shoulder the key of the house of David (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>), <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Italian Common Language Version\">ITCL</abbr> has “To him will be given full authority over the palace of David. The keys will be entrusted to him.” Similarly, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Living Translation\">NLT</abbr> says “I will give him the key to the house of David—the highest position in the royal court.”</p>\n<p>It may not be possible to speak of the key to a place, such as “the abyss” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>) in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev9:1\">REV 9:1</a> or “the kingdom of heaven” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>) in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt16:19\">MAT 16:19</a>. In such cases translators may have to say “the key to the entrance to …” or “the key used in opening or closing the gate to ….”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
